docs.abstract: The work now being taken up by large institutions has long been the purpose of many smaller ones. We spoke with seven of them.
docs.snippet: The work now being taken up by large institutions has long been the purpose of many smaller ones. We spoke with seven of them.
docs.lead_paragraph: Last year was different. Black Lives Matter, in the national psyche for nearly a decade, crested with the killing of George Floyd and weeks of widespread demonstrations that could no longer be ignored — even by classical music. Orchestras and opera companies posted statements of solidarity, however platitudinous, denouncing racism and promising a more equitable future for an industry that has historically been led by white administrators and designed to maintain a status quo that gives white artists the advantage over their underrepresented peers.

headline.main: For These Classical Musicians, It’s Always Been About Racial Equity
headline.print_headline: Where Racial Equity Is a Crucial Note

docs.lead_paragraph: HOMO IRREALIS: Essays, by André Aciman. (Farrar, Straus & Giroux, $27.) In this collection, the author of “Call Me by Your Name” and other novels contemplates the life of the imagination, and the ability to hold competing realities simultaneously in mind.

headline.main: New & Noteworthy, From ‘Faust’ to Life in Lockdown

docs.abstract: Will the Capitol riot become a super-spreader event?
docs.snippet: Will the Capitol riot become a super-spreader event?
docs.lead_paragraph: We may never know for certain without effective contact tracing — which the U.S. largely lacks — and because most of the rioters who stormed the Capitol yesterday are unidentified, tracing them would be difficult.

docs.abstract: The encounter with the Aurora, Colo., police in August was recorded on a widely shared video that showed four children lying on the ground in a parking lot, crying and screaming as several officers stood over them.
docs.snippet: The encounter with the Aurora, Colo., police in August was recorded on a widely shared video that showed four children lying on the ground in a parking lot, crying and screaming as several officers stood over them.
docs.lead_paragraph: Prosecutors in Colorado said this week that they would not charge two police officers who drew their guns and handcuffed a Black family, including two girls, after suspecting them of riding in a stolen car.

headline.main: Officers Who Handcuffed Black Family Won’t Be Charged, Prosecutors Say

docs.abstract: Some Americans are eager for a break from the constant news produced by President Trump. Others said his term had only inspired them to be more involved in activism.
docs.snippet: Some Americans are eager for a break from the constant news produced by President Trump. Others said his term had only inspired them to be more involved in activism.
docs.lead_paragraph: PITTSBURGH — For four years, David Betras has been unable to escape Donald J. Trump. The president has visited Youngstown, Ohio, the seat of Mr. Betras’s home county. So have the president’s children. People Mr. Betras had known for years became in thrall to Mr. Trump. There was no getting away on Facebook, on Instagram, at the local bar.

headline.main: ‘He Was Just Everywhere’: A Tired Country After Four Years of Trump
headline.print_headline: It’s the Dawn of an Era. The Nation Is Exhausted.

byline.original: By Campbell Robertson, Elizabeth Dias and Miriam Jordan

docs.abstract: In a first, six nongovernmental organizations are taking legal steps to force an overhaul of the country’s policing.
docs.snippet: In a first, six nongovernmental organizations are taking legal steps to force an overhaul of the country’s policing.
docs.lead_paragraph: PARIS — Six nongovernmental organizations put the French state on notice on Wednesday to force it to address “systemic discriminatory practices by the police,” a rare collective legal action that will take the government onto uncharted grounds.

headline.main: Groups Put French State on Legal Notice Over Police Racism
headline.print_headline: In a First, 6 Rights Groups Challenge France’s State Police Over Systematic Racism

docs.abstract: Some scientists fear that the mayhem on Capitol Hill may prove to have been a so-called super-spreading event.
docs.snippet: Some scientists fear that the mayhem on Capitol Hill may prove to have been a so-called super-spreading event.
docs.lead_paragraph: The mob that stormed the Capitol on Wednesday did not just threaten the heart of American democracy. To scientists who watched dismayed as the scenes unfolded on television, the throngs of unmasked intruders who wandered through hallways and into private offices may also have transformed the riot into a super-spreader event.

headline.main: A Riot Amid a Pandemic: Did the Virus, Too, Storm the Capitol?
headline.print_headline: Did the Virus, Too, Storm the Capitol Amid the Mayhem?

docs.abstract: The chief of the Capitol Police indicated he would resign after an angry mob of Trump supporters stormed past officers and into the legislative chambers.
docs.snippet: The chief of the Capitol Police indicated he would resign after an angry mob of Trump supporters stormed past officers and into the legislative chambers.
docs.lead_paragraph: Six days before a raucous rally of President Trump’s supporters in Washington, Representative Maxine Waters anxiously grilled the chief of the Capitol Police about his preparations for various scenarios: Were the rooftops secured? Would streets be blocked off? Did he know that violent groups like the Proud Boys and the Oath Keepers were vowing to stir up chaos?

headline.main: Police Failures Spur Resignations and Complaints of Double Standard
headline.print_headline: Capitol Breach Puts the Police Under Scrutiny

byline.original: By Shaila Dewan, Neil MacFarquhar, Zolan Kanno-Youngs, Ali Watkins, Christiaan Triebert, Haley Willis, Stella Cooper, Cora Engelbrecht, Evan Hill and Arielle Ray

docs.abstract: Police officers in riot gear used water cannons to disperse demonstrators in the center of Amsterdam opposed to government measures to contain the coronavirus.
docs.snippet: Police officers in riot gear used water cannons to disperse demonstrators in the center of Amsterdam opposed to government measures to contain the coronavirus.
docs.lead_paragraph: Thousands of people, some throwing fireworks and stones, joined an unauthorized protest against the Dutch government’s coronavirus restrictions in Amsterdam on Sunday, and riot police officers used water cannons, batons, attack dogs and horses to disperse the crowd.

headline.main: Dutch Police Clash With Protesters Denouncing Lockdown Measures
